<h3>Impulse</h3>
<p>

<h4>What is impulse?</h4>
<p> $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr  F{rb}{rb}{rb}$ 


<img src="{$ij.proxyPath}/static/figures/Impulse1.jpg"/>
<span class="caption">How does the final speed of a broken down car change if you apply the same force for different lengths of time?</span> 

 If we think about some real physical situations, our intuition tells us that if we apply a force to an object for longer, its final velocity will be greater.  Imagine trying to push start a car.  If the car is at rest and you begin pushing with a constant force, then the longer you keep pushing, the faster the car will be moving when you let go.</p>
<p>

 The definition or formula to calculate an impulse is simply,
$$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$  {lb}equation{rb}
As force is a vector quantity so must the impulse be a vector; Newton's second law hints at this because he tells us that it is important to consider the direction in which the impulse was applied.


<h4>But what does it mean?</h4>This formula does not give us much of a sense of what impulse {lb} actually{rb} is or what it means.  Let's go back to the idea that Newton describes in his second law of motion that {lb} an applied impulse acts to change the momentum of a body in the direction that the impulse is applied{rb}.\\

 

<img src="{$ij.proxyPath}/static/figures/Momentum1.svg"/>
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}The graph of a constant force of $10$ N applied to an object for $5$ seconds.  The impulse that the object experiences is ${lb}\vtr F{rb}{rb}{rb}$ 

 When we apply an impulse to something our intuition tells us that it will change from being at rest to moving with some speed in the direction that we applied the impulse.  By applying an impulse we will change its momentum from zero to some value given by its mass times its velocity and we would guess that the larger the impulse the greater the change in momentum.

<h5>Levels 1-4</h5>If a constant force is applied to a body for a given time then the impulse is the vector quantity given by
$$ 
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb} Impulse{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$
This relationship (equation \refimp1) shows that we can increase the magnitude of the impulse by either increasing the magnitude of the force or increasing the amount of time over which we apply the force.</p>
<p>

 So following Newton's Law,
$$
\mbox{lb}Impulse{rb}&=&\mbox{lb}change in momentum{rb}\nonumber \\
&=&\mbox{lb}final momentum{rb} - \mbox{lb}initial momentum{rb}\nonumber \\
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr F{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr v{rb}{rb}{rb}$ 
 We can now see the connection to Newton's Second Law as we learn it at school if we do a little rearrangement of our formula,
$$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr F{rb}{rb}{rb}$  $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr F{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$

 A change in velocity $(v-u)$ divided by the time it takes for that change $t$ is the average acceleration of the body, so
$$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr F{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$


