<h5>Level 5 +</h5>
<p>The simplest case, in which we can calculate an impulse, is where a constant force is applied to a body for an amount of time $t$ (as shown in figure \ref{lb}impulse1{rb}) but we might also want to consider situations where the strength of the force varies in time (figure \ref{lb}impulse2{rb}).  If the force is not constant with time then we need to calculate the total impulse applied over a given time interval to calculate the total change in momentum.  This total impulse is again equal to the area under the force-time graph.

 The geometry in our example is reasonably simple (figure \refimpulse2) so we can use the area of a triangle subtracted from the area of a rectangle to work this area out.
$$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$  $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$

 

