 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}({lb}\vtr F_f{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr F_i{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr F{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$

 To find the total impulse we need to add up all the small areas which we can do by integrating this equation for the force over time.
$$
 $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$  $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}t_f{rb}{rb}{rb}$  $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$  $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$  $\mathit{lb}\underline{lb}\boldsymbol{lb}\vtr I{rb}{rb}{rb}$ $$
We can see, therefore, that integrating the equation for the force over time produces the same result as calculating the area under the graph by triangles given by equation \refarea_tri.

